They are, but generally something like a horse is not going to get much animal protein at all in its diet. Yes, I've seen the video of the horse eating a baby chick ("Mmm! McNuggets!") but ungulate digestive systems are built for grass and leaves. Keeping horses in little stalls and feeding them starchy cattle feed with molasses is, the vets tell us, bad for them. I guess you could give a horse five pounds of raw ground beef as an experiment, but given how often horses end up getting vet visits because something they ate disagreed with their tummies, I think it might not end well. We do have classifications like "obligate carnivore" for a reason. People have tried making pet food out of plant protein. Pet cats on those diets go blind and sometimes eventually die because there isn't enough protein and they don't get the full set of amino acids in the proportions they need.

Quoted By: >>53183855
>>53183311
Beef Wellington is one of those dishes you make when you want to impress someone. It's simple in the sense that there are few ingredients, though the beef in the center needs to be really good quality, like maybe a tenderloin or ribeye. You rub it with salt and pepper and sear it on both sides in butter, then you brown some chopped or sliced mushrooms and herbs, like maybe parsley and thyme, plus optionally, some minced shallots or onions, though maybe not for these guests. This mixture is called a "duxelles" and you put some on the top of each steak, then wrap each steak in a pastry crust. Cutting or sculpting a decorative pattern on the top crust is optional, as is brushing it with egg white and sprinkling it with a bit of salt, then they go in a 400-450 degree oven for around 40 minutes to brown the pastry. It is a dish that can be as simple or as elaborate as you want it to be--you can substitute puff pastry, or wrap the beef in sliced ham, and so on--and somehow I suspect it would go over pretty well with carnivores.
